title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer XLS 1911
postcontent: The 1911 STX from the SIG SAUER Custom Shop is a two-tone 1911 that’s loaded with features. This non-railed pistol features a Nitron® slide over a Natural Stainless frame and is accented by beautiful custom burled maple grips. The slide is further accented by polished cocking serrations and a Flat Top which enhances the two-tone aspect of this pistol. The slide is topped off with adjustable combat night sights while the frame is outfitted with a magwell for fast, smooth reloads. The all stainless steel frame and slide of the STX are machined to exacting tolerances and hand-fitted to insure reliability and performance. Like all SIG SAUER products the 1911 STX pistol contains only premium internal parts including a match grade barrel, hammer/sear set and trigger. For safety the 1911 STX features a beavertail grip safety with speed bump, extended ambidextrous thumb safety, firing pin safety and hammer intercept notch and ships in a plastic gun case with cable lock and two 8-round mags. I believe this to be the best value in a custom 1911, on the market today.

title: For Sale:  Lee-Enfield L8A5 Rifle Rare 7.62 NATO
postcontent: Rare, matching and non-import marked L8A5 Lee-Enfield rifle...this rifle began life as a standard No.4 Mk.1*, manufactured at Long Branch in 1945. A late war production Long Branch, the gun was likely delivered too late for British service during the war, and presumably remained untouched in stores until selected for conversion to the NATO standard 7.62 cartridge in 1965. At the time it was hoped to convert most of the remaining No.4 rifles to the new standard chambering for emergency use, but results from the L8 programme were uninspiring and the project was shelved after only a few thousand rifles were produced at the RSAF. At the same time, an unknown quantity were converted at the unit level by armourers using kits manufactured by Sterling in Dagenham. This weapon, with Broad Arrow-mraked components and fitted with a desirable Parker-Hale PH4 adjustable sight, was likely slated for interservice competition shooting. Apparently having a very brief service life following conversion, the weapon lacks post-1968 proof marks, although it does feature the standard 'ENGLAND' export mark on the receiver ring. Undoubtedly a superior shooter, L8's are rarely seen on the collector's market, and this weapon, if left in its presesnt condition, represents a sound investment for the dedicated Enfield enthusiast. No trades but will ship
